    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-05-10T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-05-10T05:00:00-05:00" n="84"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d84">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/2769: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Italy</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Phillips</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-05-10T11:00:00+01:00"
                            >May 10, 1940—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received May 10—7:22 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>324. I called on Ciano<note n="36" xml:id="d84fn36">Count Galeazzo Ciano di
                        Cortellazzo, Italian Minister for Foreign Affairs.</note> this morning and
                    asked whether the European developments were causing any change in the Italian
                    Government’s <pb facs="0096" n="87" xml:id="pg_87"/> position as a
                    non-belligerent. I said that I had not only the responsibility of keeping you
                    accurately advised but also responsibility towards the numerous Americans
                    resident in Italy.</p>
                <p>The Minister who had come from Mussolini<note n="37" xml:id="d84fn37">Benito
                        Mussolini, Italian Prime Minister.</note> informed me that no change had
                    been decided upon or was under contemplation. While Mussolini desired to carry
                    out his obligations with Germany required by the Italo-German alliance<note
                        n="38" xml:id="d84fn38">Signed May 22, 1939, G. Fr. de Martens, <hi
                            rend="italic">Nouveau recueil général de traités</hi>, 3e sér., tome <hi
                            rend="smallcaps">xxxvii</hi>, p. 323.</note> no situation had developed
                    which called for the entry of Italy into the war. With regard to the American
                    residents in Italy he was very positive in expressing his opinion that there was
                    no need whatsoever to disturb them. He assured me that he was still hopeful that
                    Italy’s present position could be maintained in the future but he did not
                    attempt to give me any assurance in this regard.</p>
                <p>Repeated to London, Paris, Belgrade, Bern.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
